Your Honor,

I stand before you today as Robert Chapman, fully accepting my guilt in the offense of speeding. I deeply regret my actions and the danger they may have imposed on those around me.

The incident occurred the other day when I was driving my brand-new car. Fueled by curiosity about its capabilities, I made an irresponsible decision to test its speed, which led to me being caught for exceeding the speed limit. I acknowledge that this was a thoughtless and reckless act, for which I am truly sorry.

Moreover, I must admit that I failed to handle the situation responsibly after receiving the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP). I honestly did not see the NIP as I have developed a habit of neglecting my mail. It was a mistake on my part, and I understand that I should have been more diligent in managing my correspondence.

I am 26 years old and unfortunately, I already have penalty points on my license from three previous incidents involving speeding. This clearly indicates a pattern of reckless behavior on my part, and I deeply regret the choices I made in the past.

It is also important for me to disclose that I have recently been diagnosed with ADHD. While I do not offer this as an excuse for my actions, it does shed light on some of the challenges I face in making impulsive decisions and maintaining focus. For instance, not reading my mail in a timely manner can be attributed to difficulties associated with my ADHD diagnosis.

Your Honor, I want to assure you that this incident has served as a wake-up call for me. I now recognize the need to make significant changes in my behavior and take steps to prevent any future occurrences of such offenses. I am actively seeking professional help and exploring strategies to effectively manage my ADHD.

I have deeply reflected on the impact of my actions, and I am genuinely remorseful. It is my utmost desire to become a responsible, law-abiding citizen. I am committed to learning from this experience and working towards a better future.

In conclusion, I stand here today, admitting my guilt in the offense of speeding. I understand the associated consequences and am willing to face them. Furthermore, I vow to address the underlying issues that led to this offense and take necessary actions to transform myself into a responsible member of society.

Thank you for your attention.

