1174
Your Honor,

I, Robert Chapman, stand before you today with a heavy heart, fully aware of the gravity of my actions and seeking redemption for the offense of speeding. I sincerely apologize for the danger I inflicted upon others through my reckless behavior.

On the day in question, I was unable to resist the temptation of pushing the limits of my new car's speed capabilities. It was a momentary lapse in judgment, one that I deeply regret. I am thoroughly conscious of the potential harm my actions could have caused to those sharing the road with me.

I must also acknowledge my failure to respond to the Notice of Intended Prosecution (NIP) that was sent to me in the mail. In all honesty, I neglected to read my mail, and thus the NIP went unnoticed. This oversight was not intentional, but rather a result of my ongoing struggle with ADHD. I understand that this in no way excuses my negligence, but I hope it elucidates the challenges I face in managing my responsibilities effectively.

At the age of 26, I carry the burden of three previous speeding incidents on my driving record, resulting in accumulated penalty points. I recognize the significance of these prior transgressions and their impact on my driving history. I am determined to reflect upon these mistakes and make the necessary changes to ensure that I exercise better judgment on the road going forward.

In conclusion, I humbly request Your Honor's leniency and understanding as I acknowledge my wrongdoing and express my remorse for the offense of speeding. I assure you that I am committed to personal growth and positive change. I beseech Your Honor to take into consideration my genuine remorse, acknowledgement of my faults, and unwavering commitment to improved decision-making.

Thank you for your time and consideration.

Sincerely,
Robert Chapman

